# Document Processing Workflow

## CRITICAL: Phase Handoff Protocol (@file Reference)

At the END of every phase, you MUST:
1. Summarize what was done (files created/modified, stats)
2. Create the next handoff file with COMPLETE context
3. Save to tmp/handoff/phaseXX.md (e.g., phase1b.md, phase2.md, phase3.md)
4. Archive previous handoff (if exists) to tmp/handoff/history/ with timestamp
5. Tell user the EXACT command to type in the next chat

Handoff file format:
```
# Handoff: Phase [N+1] ([PHASE NAME])
## Select Model: [MODEL NAME]
## Previous Phase Summary
[what was done, files created, stats]
## Tasks for This Phase
[numbered list of specific tasks with @file references]
## Files to Reference
[list of @output/ and @review/ files]
## After This Phase
[what handoff to generate next]
```

Chat output format:
```
Phase [N] COMPLETE. [brief summary]
Files: [list]
>>> Open NEW chat, select [MODEL NAME], type:
    Execute @tmp/handoff/phaseXX.md
```

## Handoff File Detection

When user message contains "Execute @tmp/handoff/" or references a handoff file:
1. Read the handoff file completely
2. Identify which phase this is (from the file header)
3. Execute ALL tasks listed in the file
4. At the end, generate the NEXT handoff file
5. Tell user the next step

When generating handoff files:
1. Use standard format (# Handoff: Phase XX)
2. Include COMPLETE context (the next model has zero prior context)
3. Use @file references for all document paths
4. Save to tmp/handoff/phaseXX.md
5. Archive previous handoff to tmp/handoff/history/

## Available Tools Reference

### Reading & Extraction
- MCP `read_document(file_path, file_type)` - Read any document
- MCP `read_image(file_path)` - View rendered/extracted images
- MCP `convert_to_markdown(uri)` - Convert document to markdown
- Skill: doc - Auto-triggers for .docx tasks
- Skill: pdf - Auto-triggers for .pdf tasks
- Skill: spreadsheet - Auto-triggers for .xlsx tasks
- Script: scripts/extract_images.py - Extract images from docx/pdf

### Diagram Generation
- MCP `generate_diagram(code)` - Architecture/flow/sequence diagrams
- Skill: generate-architecture-diagrams - AWS/Azure/GCP + Draw.io
- Built-in: GenerateImage - Conceptual/custom visuals

### Document Assembly (all 3 formats)
- Script: scripts/template_engine.py - Fill templates (.docx/.xlsx/.pptx)
- Script: scripts/insert_images.py - Insert images into any format
- Script: scripts/word_formatter.py - Format .docx + review tracking
- Script: scripts/xlsx_formatter.py - Format .xlsx + audit columns
- Script: scripts/pptx_builder.py - Create/edit .pptx + notes tracking
- Script: scripts/render_docs.py - Render any format to PNG
- Script: scripts/strip_tracking.py - Create CLEAN from REVIEW version

## Folder Conventions
- input/          : Source files (user places here)
- output/         : Generated documents (agent places here)
                    *_REVIEW.* = with tracking, *.* = clean for client
- review/         : Review reports (GPT places here)
- tmp/handoff/    : Structured handoff files for @file reference
- tmp/images/     : Extracted images from input files
- tmp/diagrams/   : Generated diagrams before insertion
- tmp/renders/    : Rendered PNG pages for visual QA

## Author Tracking

Read config.yaml for author info. If not found, ask user for name.
Every document modification must record:
- Author name (from config.yaml)
- Model used (the model you are)
- Phase (Phase 1/1b/2/3)
- Timestamp
- Description of change

## Phase 1: CREATE Workflow (Model: Opus 4.6)

### Step 1: Analyze Input
- Scan input/ folder OR read @referenced files
- Use MCP read_document() for content preview
- Use convert_to_markdown() for structured view
- Run extract_images.py to pull images from docx/pdf into tmp/images/
- Use read_image() to view extracted images and understand their content
- Summarize available data AND images per file

### Step 2: Identify Document Type
- Check if user specified a template
- Match input content to document types in document-types.mdc
- Determine output format(s): .docx, .xlsx, .pptx, or combination

### Step 3: Plan Content Structure
- Map input data to template placeholders
- Identify what content goes where
- Note where images/diagrams are needed (use {{IMAGE:name}} placeholders)
- For images that need code-based generation: plan diagram code
- For images that need AI generation: mark as {{IMAGE:name}} for Phase 1b

### Step 4: Generate Diagrams (if needed)
- For architecture diagrams: use MCP generate_diagram()
- For complex infra diagrams: use architecture-diagrams skill
- For conceptual/custom visuals: mark as {{IMAGE:name}} for Gemini in Phase 1b
- Save all code-generated diagrams to tmp/diagrams/
- Use read_image() to verify diagram quality
- Iterate until diagrams look correct

### Step 5: Assemble Document (any format)
- Template mode: run scripts/template_engine.py
- Edit mode: use doc/spreadsheet skill or pptx_builder.py directly
- Run insert_images.py to place images/diagrams at correct positions
- Apply formatting: run word_formatter.py / xlsx_formatter.py / pptx_builder.py
- CRITICAL: Track all changes as you work, maintain a changes manifest:
  - What was added (new content, new rows, new slides)
  - What was modified (changed text, updated cells, edited slides)
  - Source of each change (which input file, which page/cell/slide)
  - Pass this manifest to the formatter scripts for review tracking

### Step 6: Apply Review Tracking + Create Dual Versions
- Run formatter with review tracking enabled:
  - Word: comments, highlights (green=new, yellow=modified), section markers, change log page
  - Excel: audit columns (_Status, _Change_Desc, _Updated_By), row colors, _Change_Log sheet
  - PPT: speaker notes tracking, footer annotations, change summary slide
- Save as REVIEW version: output/filename_REVIEW.ext
- Run scripts/strip_tracking.py to create CLEAN version: output/filename.ext
- Both versions should exist in output/

### Step 7: Visual QA Loop
- Run scripts/render_docs.py -> PNG pages (render REVIEW version)
- Use MCP read_image() to inspect each page
- Verify: images positioned, text flows, tracking is visible and correct
- Fix issues, re-render, repeat until clean

### Step 8: Deliver Draft + Generate Handoff File
- Both REVIEW and CLEAN versions saved in output/
- Clean up tmp/ files (keep tmp/handoff/)
- Report changes made (files, page counts, tables, images, tracking stats)
- Determine next phase:
  - If {{IMAGE:...}} placeholders remain -> create tmp/handoff/phase1b.md (for Gemini 3 Pro)
  - If no images needed -> create tmp/handoff/phase2.md (for GPT-5.2 High)
- Tell user: "Open NEW chat, select [MODEL], type: Execute @tmp/handoff/phaseXX.md"
- Tell reviewer: "Review the *_REVIEW version for change tracking"

## Phase 3: FIX Workflow (Model: Opus 4.6, after GPT review)

### Step 1: Read Review Report
- Read review/review_report.md
- List all findings with severity
- Ask user which items to fix (or fix all CRITICAL + HIGH by default)

### Step 2: Apply Fixes
- Fix selected items using doc skill / python-docx / openpyxl / python-pptx
- Re-apply formatting if needed
- Update review tracking: Add new comments/audit entries for fixes
  - Word: new comment "[PHASE 3] Fixed per REV-xxx: ..."
  - Excel: update _Status to "FIXED", update _Change_Desc
  - PPT: update speaker notes with fix description

### Step 3: Re-generate Dual Versions
- Update REVIEW version with fix tracking
- Re-run strip_tracking.py to regenerate CLEAN version
- Both versions now reflect all fixes

### Step 4: Re-render and QA
- Run render_docs.py on REVIEW version
- Inspect all pages -- verify fixes are correct AND tracking is updated
- Verify CLEAN version has no tracking artifacts

### Step 5: Deliver Final + Handoff
- Both output/filename_REVIEW.ext and output/filename.ext updated
- Update review report with fix status (mark items as FIXED)
- Update author tracking metadata
- Clean up tmp/ files (except handoff/)
- Generate final summary (no more phases needed)
- If user requested another iteration, generate Phase 2 prompt again
- Tell user: "Send CLEAN version to client, keep REVIEW version for records"
